d unfortunately had a very disappointing experience from start to finish.\n\nFrom the outset, we raised concerns about the condition of the existing floor and flagged that the subfloor would need to be properly leveled before new flooring and the bathtub were installed. Despite this, Tub Cove’s contractor declined to demo the old floor and instead installed the new flooring directly over the old linoleum, along with the new tub. This shortcut left a sizeable gap—large enough to fit a hand—between the tub and the floor.\n\nWhen we pointed out how unacceptable this was, the proposed “fix” was to glue a marble strip in front of the tub so “you’d never notice.” Their own response was that photos on their website only show “perfect jobs,” which was hardly reassuring. We insisted the issue be corrected.\n\nThe workmanship throughout the project was inconsistent at best. Examples included:\n\nSloppy drywall mudding that had to be redone.\n\nGaps in trim work that were cut short and nailed in anyway.\n\nCaulking that was messy and clearly not watertight.\n\nThe bathtub being damaged during installation that required repairs before it was even used due to demo work being done around the unprotected bathtub.\n\nMissing tile and incorrect estimates that caused delays.\n\nThe tile work was subbed out and not done to expectations. They had to come back twice to address tile that was installed incorrectly or cracked.\n\nWe also ended up doing significant drywall prep ourselves—work that was supposed to be included in the original scope of the contract. For this we were credited some money back.\n\nWhile one of their senior employees, Allen, was professional, efficient, and clearly skilled, he was brought in late in the project. If he had led the job from the start, things might have gone differently.\n\nOn the business side, we also encountered troubling practices. Tub Cove repeatedly pressed us for progress payments even though our contract clearly stated final payment was due upon completion. After we did pay in full, we learned their subcontractor (Alex) had not been paid for our job, despite the funds being in Tub Cove’s possession. This raised serious concerns about their financial management and created risk of a mechanic’s lien on our home. We had to initiate a dispute through American Express to protect ourselves and ensure the subcontractor was made whole.\n\nBottom line: We cannot recommend Tub Cove. The project was plagued by poor execution, shortcuts, and unprofessional handling of payments. We were advised at the outset that this work would take five days, which seemed ambitious. We expected two weeks. Instead, it took five weeks. If you are considering them, proceed with extreme caution—and insist on clear progress milestones, airtight contracts, and detailed oversight of their subcontractors.","Images":["https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/grass-cs/ANxoTn0HvoeSemNNL11QZ2KhSHgi_jpsqGkszjqbG6PKx4zrvksS5d_cUZ53JHiQ_Yrf6mqVlM35iKZm8lvtUMTRtKOTTJYHslMhxXC8mM-KpBMZhTzrg7RwB9IrKKDvv6re0mHXuzsadOV0fw0=k-no","https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/grass-cs/ANxoTn2FdT8lmPAcJ-cZML2XU1rESaeKKIrobzA9yeSFjIEiMEgKVHlP35OsYjhRXeSnwtrgLqHJvMxAatoGS98eCW4rS_HqlrI-FB1j1TdjcBraq9aUrmDUP0IFwVtnn6nLWygdWI4inEsBRQE=k-no","https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/grass-cs/ANxoTn3QToJU8iZAPbSLdjSZciB6CQwOF1gGaJuTEc0YlPWqjLiYu3Yv_aZNso_kMrq9ioCtFh5igjVnS3TktjrGiZIf0DnMzkn7pB0eG80KRL1IJgH_sJYcWUzSpkt4SLNHHDS3EGmfybxirOXr=k-no","https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/grass-cs/ANxoTn2L-9xyiXD0foWk-D_nS_lIHRP6snPF4OYT-LjUclygiwViHMw4bMegGr_9ZjM3znD0pBM687k3gC0KBxJUGDQp5JslyhuO0dDMc-_5Z6lpOOUP4w-B3lUu7q4cY_i83vd-wxWIO3WHMSut=k-no"],"When":"2025-9-10"},{"Name":"Allison Durazzi","ProfilePicture":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjVPqQXwuCp9JwYRAtTH2EI34CfD9KVHAt9G0vaNUNmno_o2U72u=s120-c-rp-mo-ba2-br100","Rating":3,"Description":"I wish I could recommend this company as there are some kind folks who work there. Unfortunately, the person who did our installation did not do a good job and did not clean up after the job was done. When he came out to fix the failed laminate, he apologized for not cleaning up after himself. But then when he was done, he asked me if he’d cleaned to my satisfaction — and argued with me when I pointed out the adhesive he’d dropped on the tub. He then accused “somebody” (i.e., my husband or me) of sabotaging his original work.\n\nThe work involved removing ceramic tile. Not cleaning up meant that there were shards of ceramic left throughout our bathroom, foyer, and down the hall of my building. This was a safety hazard. Since the mess followed him out to the parking lot, I had to clean after him so that it did not cause injury to my neighbors or result in me getting a fine from my homeowner’s association.\n\nWhile the product itself has been fixed and looks fine, I did not appreciate having to clean up after the worker or dealing with his unprofessional interactions—especially since I’d expressed reservations about having the same person come back to repair.\n\nI shared my concerns of the second visit and asked for consideration of my time in the final bill on 4/9/18. Shelley at TubCove agreed the behavior was unacceptable and that she would forward my concerns to the company owner in Arizona. I have yet to receive a response but will update this review should I hear back.\n\nUPDATED: I changed my rating from 2 to 3 stars. TubCove's owner called me to apologize for the service we received from the installer. During our conversation, he said they talked with the installer who admitted to skipping \"a critical step\" in the installation, which resulted in the failure of the product. They refunded me $150.","Images":["https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/grass-cs/ANxoTn03lTrWzsb_vq1OCbhp7AOwk_rW0trN8iySItGVXv5OOMflv2eASK0qtIRqE5Ce-gihWS02sx3gzzRD2qdpS5uIXxZHq7Tq_zPkoha81tZDzOLjrWcR31143D6cUkUQlHHIRX8Wpg=k-no","https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/grass-cs/ANxoTn2lz5J1R5JMO1n9UFU-T_yOG2nFSdeiCOSt-vpl6bvOJ8sLktbQOV7